          "This is where Avana’s model becomes especially relevant. LP positions are not static collateral. Their value depends on the underlying assets, the shape of the pool, fee accrual, and, in concentrated liquidity systems, the active range of the position itself. A looping strategy built on top of LP collateral therefore needs a framework that understands more than headline market value. It needs a system that treats the position as something live and path dependent. That is one of the core reasons Avana is being designed around LP specific valuation, risk treatment, and liquidation logic on top of Aave v4. Looping only becomes credible when the collateral model itself is more aware of how LP positions behave.",
          "The safest form of looping is usually modest. A user may borrow a relatively small amount against a supported LP position and redeploy it into a second yield source without pushing the original collateral close to its borrowing limit. In this structure, the borrowed capital is not meant to maximize exposure. It is meant to improve capital efficiency while preserving room for error. For many users, especially early on, that is the right way to think about looping. It is a controlled extension of the original position rather than a recursive bet on perfect market conditions.",
          "More advanced versions of looping can involve redeploying borrowed capital back into liquidity itself. That can increase fee generation in favorable environments, but it also makes the structure more reflexive. The user is no longer only exposed to one LP position and one debt balance. They are exposed to a layered structure in which price movement, collateral quality, and debt safety all interact more aggressively. This can work, but only if the user has a clear understanding of how much margin actually exists and what happens when the underlying assumptions break. In these setups, leverage does not merely amplify returns. It amplifies the speed at which a healthy position can become a stressed one.",
